<p align="center"><font face="Arial" size="+2" color="#006666"><b><a name="top"></a>Water: The thirty anomalies of water</b></font><a href="#1a"><sup>1</sup></a></p>
<p><br>
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="1"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Melting point"> melting point</a>. [<a href="explan.html#Mpt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="2"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Boiling point">boiling
    point</a>. [<a href="explan.html#Bpt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="3"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Critical point">critical point</a>. [<a href="explan.html#Cpt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="4"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Surface tension">surface tension</a>. [<a href="explan.html#ST">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="5"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Viscosity">viscosity</a>. [<a href="explan.html#Visc">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="6"></a>Water has
unusually high <a href="data.html#Enthalpy of Vaporization">heat of vaporization</a>. [<a href="explan.html#vap">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="7"></a>Water shrinks on melting. [<a href="explan.html#melt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="8"></a>Water has a high density that increases on heating (up to
    3.984イ). [<a href="explan.html#density">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="9"></a>The number of nearest
    neighbors increases
    on melting.
    [<a href="explan.html#neig">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="10"></a>The number of nearest
    neighbors increases with temperature.
    [<a href="explan.html#neig">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="11"></a>Pressure reduces
its melting point (13.35 MPa gives a melting point of -1イ) [<a href="explan.html#Pmelt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p style="line-height: 100%; margin-top: 4; margin-bottom: 8"><font face="Arial"><a name="12"></a>Pressure reduces
    the temperature of maximum density. [<a href="explan.html#Pdens">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="13"></a>D<sub>2</sub>O
    and
T<sub>2</sub>O differ from H<sub>2</sub>O in their physical properties much more
    than might be expected from their increased mass; e.g. they have increasing temperatures of maximum
    density (11.185イ and 13.4イ respectively). [<a href="explan.html#Isotope">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="14"></a>Water shows an
    unusually large viscosity increase as the temperature is lowered. [<a href="explan.html#Tvisc">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="15"></a>Water's viscosity decreases with pressure
(at temperatures below 33イ). [<a href="explan.html#Pvisc">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="16"></a>Water has
unusually low compressibility. [<a href="explan.html#comp">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="17"></a>The
    compressibility drops
    as temperature increases (below a minimum at about 46.5イ). [<a href="explan.html#Tcomp">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="18"></a>Water
    has a low coefficient of expansion (thermal expansivity). [<a href="explan.html#expan">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="19"></a>Water's
    thermal expansivity reduces
    increasingly (becoming negative) at low temperatures. [<a href="explan.html#Texpan">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="20"></a>The speed of
    sound increases with temperature (up to a maximum at 73イ). [<a href="explan.html#sound">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p style="line-height: 100%; margin-top: 4; margin-bottom: 8"><font face="Arial"><a name="21"></a>Water has over
    twice the <a href="data.html#CP"> specific heat</a>  capacity of ice or steam. [<a href="explan.html#Cv">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="22"></a>The <a href="data.html#CP"> specific heat</a>
    capacity (C<sub>P</sub> and C<sub>V</sub>) is unusually high. [<a href="explan.html#Cp">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="23"></a>The <a href="data.html#CP"> specific heat</a>
    capacity (C<sub>P</sub>) has a minimum (36イ). [<a href="explan.html#Cpmin">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="24"></a>NMR
    spin-lattice relaxation are very small at low temperatures. [<a href="explan.html#NMR">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p style="line-height: 100%; margin-top: 4; margin-bottom: 8"><font face="Arial"><a name="25"></a>Solutes have varying effects on properties such as density and viscosity.
    [<a href="explan.html#Solute">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="26"></a>None
    of its solutions even approach thermodynamic ideality; even D<sub>2</sub>O
    in H<sub>2</sub>O is not ideal. [<a href="explan.html#ideal">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="27"></a>X-ray diffraction shows an unusually detailed structure.
    [<a href="explan.html#X-ray">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="28"></a>Supercooled water has two phases and a
    <a href="data.html#Second critical point"> second critical point</a> at
-45イ. [<a href="explan.html#2Cpt">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a name="29"></a>Liquid water
    is easily supercooled down to about -25イ and with more difficulty down to
    about -38イ with further supercooling possible, in tiny droplets, down to
    about -70イ. Supercooled liquid water can be produced from glassy amorphous
    ice between -123イ and - 149イ [<a href="ref.html#74" name="74">74</a>] and may
    coexist with cubic ice up to -63イ [<a href="ref.html#137" name="137">137</a>]. [<a href="explan.html#cool">explanation</a>]</font></li>
  <li>
    <p><font face="Arial"><a href="phase.html" name="30">Solid
    water</a> exists in a wider variety of stable (and metastable) crystal and
    amorphous structures than other materials. [<a href="explan.html#ice">explanation</a>]</font></li>
</ol>
    <p><br>
    
